# Architecture Boundary Rules

## Applicability

Apply this rule when changing:

- module dependencies
- public API or SPI
- package ownership
- Spring Boot auto-configuration
- servlet or WebFlux integration
- OpenTelemetry agent/SDK integration
- JMX/OpenMBean adapters
- runtime control
- wire protocols
- shared infrastructure abstractions
- Gradle project structure

Before editing, inspect the actual module graph, public consumers, custom source sets, tests, and current architecture gates.

## Primary Boundary Model

The tracing platform uses explicit ownership boundaries:

```text
application code
    -> platform-tracing-api
    -> platform-tracing-otel
    -> Spring / Web / OTel / JMX adapters
    -> external runtime and telemetry infrastructure
```

Do not collapse these layers for convenience.

## API Boundary

`platform-tracing-api` owns:

- application-facing contracts
- intentional SPIs
- immutable value objects
- specifications and builders
- public annotations
- classloader-neutral wire/control vocabulary
- public result and violation models

It must not own:

- runtime implementation
- Spring Boot wiring
- servlet or WebFlux types
- JMX/OpenMBean implementation
- OTel SDK implementation
- exporters or processors
- domain validation
- sampling or scrubbing algorithms
- mutable live state

The API module must not depend on core.

## Core Boundary

`platform-tracing-otel` owns:

- implementations of public contracts
- runtime behavior
- lifecycle
- domain validation
- sampling and scrubbing policies
- runtime-control handlers
- atomic state transitions
- last-known-good state
- no-op behavior
- safety invariants

Core must not depend on:

- Spring Boot
- `ApplicationContext`
- `@ConfigurationProperties`
- servlet APIs
- WebFlux/Reactor adapter APIs
- JMX/OpenMBean transport types

## Spring Boundary

Spring Boot modules own:

- bean wiring
- typed configuration properties
- conditional registration
- startup diagnostics
- Actuator integration
- mapping startup configuration into core contracts

They must not own:

- tracing algorithms
- wire decoding
- domain validation
- sampling/scrubbing implementation
- runtime-control state transitions
- JMX transport behavior

Do not use Spring as a service locator for core runtime behavior.

## Servlet and WebFlux Boundaries

Servlet and WebFlux adapters must remain isolated.

Forbidden:

- servlet adapter -> WebFlux adapter
- WebFlux adapter -> servlet adapter
- servlet types in reactive modules
- Reactor/WebFlux types in servlet modules
- ThreadLocal-only context assumptions in reactive flows

Shared behavior may move to API, core, or common auto-configuration only when it is genuinely framework-neutral.

## OTel and JMX Boundary

OTel/JMX modules own:

- Java agent and SDK bridges
- sampler, processor, exporter, and provider integration
- JMX/OpenMBean adapters
- classloader-sensitive wiring

They must not:

- become a second domain core
- expose implementation classes through public API
- leak JMX/OpenMBean or OTel SDK implementation types into application-facing contracts
- duplicate domain validation already owned by core

## Starter Boundary

Starters are thin dependency aggregators.

They must not contain:

- business logic
- runtime algorithms
- domain validation
- duplicate auto-configuration
- environment-specific orchestration
- mutable global state
- hidden startup side effects

A starter may select the intended integration path and dependencies only.

## Expected Dependency Direction

```text
platform-tracing-otel
    -> platform-tracing-api

platform-tracing-spring-boot-autoconfigure
    -> platform-tracing-api
    -> platform-tracing-otel

platform-tracing-autoconfigure-webmvc
    -> approved API/core/autoconfigure modules

platform-tracing-autoconfigure-webflux
    -> approved API/core/autoconfigure modules

platform-tracing-otel-extension
    -> approved API/core modules

starters
    -> matching integration and auto-configuration modules

tests, samples, benchmarks, and E2E
    -> production modules under test
```

## Forbidden Dependency Directions

Do not introduce:

- API -> core
- core -> Spring
- WebMVC -> WebFlux
- WebFlux -> servlet
- production -> test/sample/benchmark/E2E
- API -> JMX/OpenMBean implementation
- API -> OTel SDK implementation without an approved contract
- circular dependencies
- runtime module -> starter
- domain policy -> transport adapter

Do not solve cycles by:

- changing `implementation` to `api`
- making helpers public
- introducing static holders
- moving domain logic into auto-configuration
- duplicating contracts

Fix ownership.

## Public Surface

Every public type must be classified as one of:

1. application-facing API
2. external SPI
3. wire/control contract
4. public-for-compilation internal bridge
5. accidental public type to remove

The default for a new type is package-private.

A public-for-compilation internal bridge must:

- be documented as internal
- have a narrow consumer allowlist
- be protected by ArchUnit or equivalent
- not appear in application-facing documentation

Do not create public helpers merely to cross subpackages.

## Classloader Boundary

Application and agent code may use different classloaders.

Across the boundary:

- use JDK-only wire types
- use explicit schemas
- use String wire values instead of Java enum instances
- avoid implementation-class casts
- avoid shared static holders
- isolate JMX/OpenMBean types in adapters
- do not use Java native serialization
- test real classloader behavior

Do not pass Spring or OTel SDK implementation objects across the boundary.

## Control Protocol Boundary

Preserve:

```text
wire payload
    -> structural decode
    -> domain validation
    -> mutation policy
    -> apply or read
```

Ownership:

- API: wire vocabulary and structural validation
- Core: domain validation and state transitions
- Adapter: JMX/OpenMBean conversion and transport

Do not reintroduce:

- raw wire-map application
- domain rules in the API decoder
- public internal schema/validator
- dual legacy/new decode paths
- transport types in core/API contracts

## Shared Code

Shared code is acceptable only when it represents a genuinely shared stable concept.

Do not create:

- `Utils`
- `Common`
- `Shared`
- giant helper modules
- catch-all base classes
- generic managers
- platform-wide registries

Prefer:

- domain-specific packages
- narrow internal services
- explicit contracts
- duplication over a false shared abstraction when ownership differs

A shared abstraction must reduce real semantic duplication, not just line count.

## Side Effects and Coupling

Hidden side effects are architecture violations.

Review:

- static initialization
- bean construction
- background threads
- JMX registration
- global OTel mutation
- exporter creation
- filesystem access
- network access
- system-property mutation

Side effects must be:

- explicitly owned
- lifecycle-managed
- idempotent where needed
- reversible where practical
- observable
- tested

Do not use hidden callbacks, reflection, or framework lookup to cross boundaries.

## Pre-Production Policy

The tracing solution is pre-production.

Breaking module, package, API, SPI, bean, property, or dependency changes are allowed when they materially improve ownership and final architecture.

Prefer direct migration and deletion over:

- compatibility aliases
- forwarding modules
- deprecated bridges
- duplicate contracts
- dual implementation paths

A breaking boundary change must still migrate all consumers, tests, custom source sets, samples, docs, and build logic.

Do not use pre-production status to justify arbitrary module churn.

## Architecture Fitness

Protect boundaries with executable rules where practical.

Verify:

- API does not depend on core
- core does not depend on Spring
- servlet and WebFlux remain isolated
- JMX/OpenMBean absent from API
- OTel SDK implementation absent from API
- internal helpers are not public
- starters remain thin
- legacy packages and symbols do not return
- raw wire payload cannot reach apply
- domain validation remains in core
- production modules do not depend on test modules
- dependency cycles fail the build

Do not weaken a gate to make generated code compile.

## Verification

For boundary changes:

1. compile affected modules
2. compile affected test and custom source sets
3. run focused tests
4. run module taxonomy and architecture fitness gates
5. inspect dependency reports when Gradle edges change
6. run full build for module/publication changes
7. run E2E for classloader, JMX, agent, servlet, WebFlux, or runtime-control boundaries

A final report must include:

```text
Boundary changed:
Old ownership:
New ownership:
Dependency edges added/removed:
Public API/SPI impact:
Classloader impact:
Migration:
Architecture gates:
Tests and E2E:
Residual risks:
```

Use `PASS`, `PASS_WITH_WARNINGS`, `INSUFFICIENT_EVIDENCE`, or `FAIL` based on executed evidence.
